vectorData.altText: 27. From which body regions does the thoracic duct collect lymph? Choose all that apply.
That's right!  Lymph from these regions drains into the thoracic duct.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Lymphatic capillaries coalesce repeatedly, forming progressively larger lymphatic vessels called lymphatic trunks that ultimately converge to form the largest lymphatic vessels in the body, the lymphatic ducts. Lymphatic ducts empty into the great veins in the neck. 
The thoracic duct is the largest lymphatic vessel in the body. As illustrated by the darker shaded area in accompanying diagram, it collects lymph bilaterally from tissues below the diaphragm     , and conducts it superiorly. In the posterior thorax, the thoracic duct collects lymph bilaterally from the thoracic wall. 
In the neck, near its terminus, the thoracic duct accepts lymph from the left side of the head and neck via the left jugular trunk, from the left upper limb via the left subclavian trunk, and from the left thoracic viscera via the left bronchomediastinal trunk. 
From the thoracic duct, lymph from these three quadrants of the body drains into venous blood at the left venous angle, which is the convergence of the left internal jugular vein     with the left subclavian vein    .
drains venous blood from the left upper limb and axilla
drains venous blood from the left side of the head and neck
i.e. the lower limbs, the pelvis and perineum, and the abdomen
